{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567544"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:04:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:04:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19128"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19128"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.06,0.16,0.2,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11862"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87038"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11862"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71295"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"9364"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28033"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87038"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her general practice clinic with a three day history of clear fluid draining from her right nostril. She had endoscopic sinus surgery two weeks ago. She reports the drainage is worse when bending forward. She has no fever or neck stiffness. Her medical history includes chronic rhinosinusitis. She takes regular budesonide nasal spray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination clear fluid can be seen draining from the right nostril when she leans forward. Neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glucose dipstick testing of fluid","Fluorescein dye testing","Magnetic resonance imaging","Computed tomography scan","Beta-2 transferrin testing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) rhinorrhoea following endoscopic sinus surgery. The clear fluid drainage that worsens with position changes (reservoir sign) is characteristic of CSF leak. Confirming the diagnosis is crucial for appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-2 transferrin testing\u003C/strong\u003E is considered the gold standard for confirming CSF leaks. This protein is almost exclusively found in CSF, perilymph, and aqueous humour, making it highly specific for CSF detection. The test has a sensitivity and specificity approaching 100%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose dipstick testing\u003C/strong\u003E of the fluid, while historically used, is unreliable. CSF glucose levels overlap significantly with those of nasal secretions and tears, leading to both false positive and false negative results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E scanning can help localise a bony defect but cannot definitively confirm that draining fluid is CSF. It would typically be performed after confirming CSF leak to plan surgical repair.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E may help identify the site of CSF leak but is not the most appropriate first-line investigation to confirm the diagnosis. It is most useful for surgical planning once the diagnosis is confirmed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluorescein dye testing\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure requiring intrathecal administration of fluorescein. While it can be useful for localising the precise site of CSF leak during surgery, it is not appropriate as an initial diagnostic test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce a CSF leak is confirmed, management typically involves bed rest with head elevation, avoidance of straining activities, and possible surgical repair if conservative measures fail. Patients should be monitored for signs of meningitis, as they are at increased risk of ascending infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta-2 transferrin testing is the gold standard for confirming cerebrospinal fluid leakage","Clear fluid draining from the nose or ear should raise suspicion for cerebrospinal fluid leak, particularly after trauma or surgery","Glucose testing of clear fluid is unreliable for diagnosing cerebrospinal fluid leaks"],"references":["Murali M. Beta 2 Transferrin (B2T) as a Biomarker of Cerebrospinal Fluid (CSF) Rhinorrhoea. The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology. 2009; Volume 123(2): S169. Available at: https://www.jacionline.org/article/S0091-6749(08)03059-5/fulltext","Nandapalan V, Watson ID, Swift AC. Beta-2-transferrin and cerebrospinal fluid rhinorrhoea. Clin Otolaryngol Allied Sci. 1996 Jun;21(3):259-64. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8818499/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71295"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19128"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71295"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-25T15:04:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-25T15:04:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11862"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87038"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"